tip.text:
Take yourself to the quaint village that is Clapton, give your moustache a good twirl and then squeeze your bum into a seat in this wee crêperie - or if the weather is nice come find us amongst the lavender outback. Now listen carefully dearies; the menu is broken up into crêpes and galettes. Galettes are made with buckwheat flour, water and salt - nothing else, which makes them crunchy and a little nutty to taste. They are then topped with all manner of proper French goodies, from homemade ratatouille and blue cheese sauce to Bayonne ham with sautéed potatoes and Reblochon (one of the smelliest of the cheeses).

The list of crepes is - we are pleased to say - almost as long as the savouries. Standouts are flambéed pear, chocolate sauce and vanilla ice cream or if you're feeling a little fancy try the sugar, fresh orange and lemon juice with a generous swig of Grand Marnier. Ooft yes please Mr French guy!

There’s a definite beauty in simple pleasures. Kicking back and listening to wax spin while you sip on a coffee has got to be one of those: swing by here and listen to records in a supremely chilled setting, with coffee from the delightful roasters at All Press and fresh juices on the menu to boot. Drinks might get a little bit stiffer once the sun goes down but you won’t find us complaining about that.

This Japanese joint on a Clapton back street is simplicity personified (restaurantified?). Take a seat at the sunken sharing tables (shoes off, of course) or a stool by the window and flick through the short menu. It's sushi, sashimi and nigiri on one section; skewers and hot delicacies on another; and a page at the back for nibbles and puddings. The limited options and simple descriptions give you time to really think about what you'd like to feast on - although our answer is usually 'everything'.

The softshell crab sushi is a real winner; as is the tuna sashimi which comes as three thick slabs of succulent pink fish. As for the hots, we'd tip the grilled mackerel skewers with a tangy sweet vinegar - one of the nicest mouthfuls of fish we'd had in a while. Everything feels straight forward and well considered, and sipping a crisp Japanese lager between each course is a truly pleasurable experience.

listing.name: St John at Hackney Brewery x Ela
listing.subtitle: Beautiful Beer & Cypriot Kebabs

tip.text:
A brewery and food joint in a renovated railway arch might not have you rubbing your eyes in shock, but there's plenty more to this place than meets those eyes. Ostensibly, it's a brewery and taproom with a rotating kitchen out back, but the attention to detail here is quite a sight - from the way they make their beer in vats that would have Walter White raising his eyebrows, to the understated beauty of their huge window facade and the 200-year-old church pews that line the walls.

The result is a damn fine place to have a high quality beer (they have 11 lagers, ales and stouts on tap) and get full. It's also deeply rooted in the community, with heavy involvement in local projects in collab with the church of the same name.

Out back is a kitchen currently inhabited by Ela, creators of simple, incredibly tasty Cypriot food. Inspired by the 'world's best kebab shop' in Cyprus, their 'babs come in wondrously marinated chicken, pork or halloumi variations stuffed full of slaws, feta, currents and salads. Big enough to share, these are truly tasty bites. Add in a nice sun-trap garden and hefty speakers and you've got a suitable spot to kick back and let some nice times roll.

If you’re wondering if this Breaking Bad-themed cocktail bar is all gimmick, we should say: it is. But it has enough attention to detail, enough interactivity, and enough cool shit going on that it transcends what could just exist as a clickbait FB video and becomes a place that we might actually recommend. The whole thing is built into an RV truck like the one from the show; you’ll don yellow safety suits, grab a welcome cocktail of crystal meth (a mojito in a flask with a syringe of blue liquid) and take a seat somewhere in the meth lab caravan. The menu takes you straight back to your GCSEs with Bunsen burners, test tubes, and neon-coloured alcoholic beverages.

The cocktails are a little sweet for our tastes but the fun here is the spectacle: using dry ice to create vanilla smoke to infuse our peach liquor with; using syringes and an electric pump to make white chocolate foam; and best/weirdest of all - a bowl of Kahlúa-milk Rice Crispies. It’s an experience, and for £35 quid for two hours and three cocktails, is just inside the realms of not a bump.

Outside of the RV they’ve got another bar, vegan pizzas, a pumping hip hop soundtrack, and arcade machines where you’ll be awarded a shot depending on your score. Oh, and the whole place is vegan. Seriously there’s a lot going on at this place, and we’re still trying to wrap our heads around it all. Or maybe we actually just took meth and this was all some fever-dream. Is anyone else itchy?

It may seem like everyone and their grandma is transforming an abandoned East End railway arch into something or other, but you can't fault Night Tales for their ambition. Set in two arches and an accompanying outdoor area that encompass almost 6,000 square feet, this is a huge Hackney hangout spot offering plenty. There's an Asahi beer garden, covered and heated seating areas, live music from a 300-capacity club space, a large cocktail bar, a beer shack, an in-house Japanese Izakaya restaurant (Fat Baby) and pizza (Sons of Slice).

They've battened down the hatches for winter, covering their huge covered terrace and adding some fire pits, candles and, fear not, dependable heaters pumping out warmth. Just don't think too much about that energy bill. Liable to get lively on weekend evenings, head here for a little hibernation, Hackney style.

We could spend all day in this incredible store. And, luckily, we can. A coffee shop and fully-stocked bar enable round-the-clock fun (parties, exhibitions, illustration classes and open-mic nights). This feels like the kind of venture you should support, a place with real soul.

You’ll find wow-inducing women’s clothing, shoes and accessories from 1900s–80s. It’s great for dresses and there are even some bridal bits. Expect an in-house tailor and seamstress specialising in vintage alterations and a personal shopper on hand too. Upstairs the men’s selection is slightly smaller but still cool. Come for the clobber, stay for the cocktails.

Strolling up towards this restaurant you’ll pretty likely go ‘oooooooo’ as you see Silver Lining standing proud next to its sister bar Every Cloud. We see what ya did there, veeery clever. Silver Lining is the new venture of Alistair Maddox, aka, the guy who ran Broadway Market for a decade, so it's to be expected that the food is going to be up to it.

The concept is small seasonal plates, and the vibe is light & airy. Kick back and tuck into dishes such as their bavette steak with Padron red pepper sauce, or their jerk chicken scotch eggs with mango and papaya hot sauce. To wash it all down, they've got their famous tipple from Every Cloud on hand. Cocktail big dogs such as their Every Cloud Rusty Nail and Every Cloud Negroni are making the rounds, and should not be missed under *any* circumstance.

Remember that sexy menu at Peg + Patriot? Well we do. And so does Matt Whiley (aka The Talented Mr Fox) 'cause he put it together. He got a food waste shaped bee in his bonnet and decided to set up a cocktail bar that's all about reducing it. How? Using only sustainable ingredients, distilling, fermenting and brewing in an on-site 'lab' and waging war on straws.

You too can fight the good fight, in a more relaxed manner, by slurping on his seasonal cocktails. Think strawberry wine, lemon balm gin and whey, or the fresher carrot, hemp seed and liquorice. Soak it up with sourdough and homemade kohlrabi or pickled celeriac and truffle and you might as well be at a spa. Sort of.

Moth Club - short 'of course' for The Memorable Order of Tin Hats - is a wondrously kitsch time warp of a boozer and event space. It’s a glittery mash-up of two cultural scenes colliding: an ex-servicemen’s club whose members still shoot the shit and play darts in the old bar whilst a sprightly and unsightly blend of Hackney young’uns come and embrace a lil' joyous abandon.

Nice indie gigs, 80s nights, bingo, themed quizzes (Peep Show, Ru Paul, Simpsons...) and film screenings take place under the gold glittered ceiling, amid red velvet booths and the iconic red and black chequered floor. Yep it's got the aesthetic, but it's also got the kind of welcoming vibe that’ll have you spinning around to Abba at midnight without a care in the goddamn world.

Nope, the grimy, iconic Dalston namesake is not setting up a restaurant off-shoot. This cosy little nook - quite like a nest in fact - is the baby of three pals who had been searching for a place to call their home after conquering the pop-up and festival food scene. And they've done a terrific job of it, with a short menu offering beautifully crafted small dishes, either a la carte or on a set menu, that compliment the warm interiors and grooving soundtrack. It's an excellent date-night spot.

The solo chef chooses one meat to work with at a time and bases his dishes around it - we were lucky enough to find duck in the kitchen, and while we're not quite sure how he created the duck steamed pudding, we're awful glad he did. That, and with the crispy garlic potato cake and the celeriac and truffle tart, would be our highlights. With the three owners drifting about the place, this feels very much like a passion project. It's the kind of place to enjoy when you're not in a hurry, when you can sit back over a couple of hours, taking each meticulous dish as it comes.

Isreali-inspired Bernstein’s Bar is a slice of Tel-Aviv cool sitting on a corner of Chatsworth Road. This is an ideal place to take a seat (inside or on the pavement) and watch the Clapton cool cats pass whilst tucking into hearty Middle Eastern dishes; having a coffee; doing the lazy lunch dance; or dipping the beak in something strong and letting the evening take over.

Sourcing plenty of their bits locally, the cuisine here is the comforting chow of Israel and the Levant: fish, meat and cheese sharing boards alongside filling and tasty soups - the chicken stew is known to cure almost every illness known to man. Serving all sorts for all sorts, it’s another vibey spot to add to Clapton’s growing arsenal.

All the silver linings here with strong drinks, low lights and good times. This cosy, quaint and intimate little spot is located right around the corner from Hackney Empire and features your perfect East Laandan cocktail list, including a monthly rejig of the classic old fashioned.

Once you've chosen your poison from the witty (if a little try hard) menu, prepare to be impressed. We like a sherry heavy menu so went for the 'Sherry Woo Woo'. We're fully on board with making sherry cool again. Maybe that should be our new slogan.

The unremarkable door leading to a dark flight of stairs next to the Spar on Chatsworth Road does little to prepare you for the eye-popping beauty that awaits at the top. You’ll enter into a dimly lit bar where speckled mirrors, a sweeping curved ceiling, copper pineapple bar lamps and plush, chesterfield benches will transport you through time and space to 1920s Hollywood, and a rendezvous with someone glamorous and seductive. Or that dude you met on Happn.

The art deco aesthetic continues into the theatre where an abundance of red velvet and extremely comfortable armchairs will settle you in nicely. The only risk is feeling so at home that you end up falling asleep - especially with the recommended carafe of Borough Wines’ malbec. £5 tickets on Monday’s ain’t bad either.

This one is a real goody, what you might call a 'big name on campus'. After a series of stand out supper clubs, the guys behind Pidgin nestled down in Hackney to great acclaim, earning themselves a well deserved Michelin star.

Head down to this cosy, simply decorated restaurant for a weekly changing set menu. Costing £49 it displays some truly great British grub served with a pinch of international-inspired ideas. It's a set menu, you'll eat what you're given - but fear not, the food here is seasonal, delicate and exquisite. If you're feeling really extra, the wine pairing is an absolute treat too.

Tucked away behind Hackney’s Wilton Way, Wolfie’s is a teeny tiny, dog-friendly bar - there’s space for about 15 so we reckon it’s got to be E8’s smallest drinking hole. Luckily there's plenty of pavement overspill space in the summertime.

It's the perfect spot to enjoy a glass of biodynamic orange wine and a selection of charcuteries, but the cocktail list is banging too; we rate the White Wolfgroni, made with suze, gin and white vermouth. A masterclass in flattering lighting and artfully distressed decor, Wolfie’s is only open Thursday to Sunday evenings. Hot tip: pop down on Sundays for some candle-lit live music and good vibes.

Formerly the rather ramshackle London Fields Pub, this building has had a significant refurb to become Martello Hall: a three storey townhouse that serves as a cocktail bar, restaurant, workspace and on-the-go coffeehouse. Plenty of dough has been spent on the stripped-back decor and vintage furniture, and the result is a pretty swanky and classy joint.

Food wise, it's mostly Italian fare with sharing plates and a wood fire oven for delicious pizzas. We'd particularly recommend the Number 7, with roast squash & beetroot, ricotta, hazelnuts, beetroot pesto, mint and kale. Upstairs, you'll find a cosy lounge area with decks and a cocktail bar, which seems an ideal place to woo and be wooed as the night unfolds.

What else? You can hot desk here and work, and also grab coffee or sausage roll by the inch from their street hatch.

El Garito is so darn discreet you’re half expecting the bartender to give you a round of applause for finding it when you come through the door. It's a diminutive, angular nook that feels like it might have been a broom-closet before someone had the bright idea to turn it into a romantic lil' money maker. And it is romantic and very, very intimate - if you've got secrets you don't want strangers knowing, don't come here and let that tongue get loose.

Cocktails is the rub, and the menu is reassuringly short - five or six very different, strong concoctions to be enjoyed on a high stool, whilst appearing wistful. Dim, dark and cosy, it's got the special 'hidden gem' vibe that would make it ideal for the first or second date flex. We did spy the charcuterie but would probably tip just sticking to the drinks.

listing.name: The Taproom at London Fields Brewery
listing.subtitle: Craft Beer & Bites

tip.text: This is the taproom of the London Fields Brewery empire, and a deceptively good place to enjoy one of LFB's damn fine craft beers on tap or some beer-friendly grub. That food has a decidedly German influence: indulgent dishes like schnitzel, beer-cheese dumplings and a halloumi beetroot burger all feature on the weekend menu. It's a fairly simple affair inside with a stripped back aesthetic, but this place is not just about beer - you'll also find organic wine, cocktails and live jazz on Sundays.

If there was any doubt about the level of cash being splashed in London Fields, Mare Street Market is the definitive proof. In a huge, ornately decorated space, this is a curated 'best of' selection of Hackney businesses: coffee from Flying Horse Coffee; (expensive) flowers from Rebel Rebel; vinyl from Stranger Than Paradise records; a rotating pop up shop selling something artisan and expensive; an antique furniture shop; a deli; and both an open kitchen and restaurant.

With all that under one roof, this is most certainly set to become a blue-tick-verified Hackney hangout. Not a place to come if you're a little strapped, but if you want to sample some top quality produce, see a venue with a super high attention to detail, or just kick it somewhere pleasant, it's definitely worth your time.
